As Leigh wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/17/2004 at 08:24:40 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>I am trying to standardize the manner in which timed test results are 
>listed in a table where I work.  In some cases, it is sufficient to 
>list that the test was greater than a given number of minutes.  in 
>those cases, should there be a space between the greater than symbol 
>(e.g., "> 2 minutes") or not (e.g., ">2 minutes").  I know it is 
>appropriate to include spaces in an equation as in, "8b > 5".  
>However, the space doesn't look right in the scenario I am 
>presenting.  I know it sounds somewhat silly but I don't want to ask 
>my employees to do something that flies in the face of standard math 
>protocol.  Thanks.
>
>[Difficulty]
>
>
>[Thoughts]
>

Hello Leigh,

The standard practice is to put some space around things like + , >, or >= signs.

x > 2,

not 

x>2.

However, I think you can do exactly as you wish and it won't offend any but the most 
persnickety.


